Story 1 – App Shell, Navigation & Material Design Base

Goal

Create the core application shell with routing and a minimal Material Design–inspired design system so that subsequent features (including the Journal view) can plug into a consistent layout and component library.

⸻

Scope
	1.	Project Setup & Dependencies
	•	Ensure the project is created with:
	•	Vue 3 (Composition API)
	•	Vite
	•	TypeScript (configured with `strict: true` in tsconfig.json for better type safety)
	•	TailwindCSS
	•	Add and configure:
	•	Vue Router
	•	Pinia
	•	Dexie (for IndexedDB operations)
	•	Confirm existing tooling is in place or add if missing:
	•	ESLint (Vue + TypeScript)
	•	Prettier
	•	Vitest with Vue Test Utils and @testing-library/vue (configure a basic test setup file)
	2.	Routing & Base Views
	•	Configure Vue Router with the following routes:
	•	/ (default route) – redirects to /journal
	•	/today
	•	/journal
	•	/emotions
	•	/exercises
	•	/profile
	•	Create placeholder view components:
	•	TodayView.vue
	•	JournalView.vue
	•	EmotionsView.vue
	•	ExercisesView.vue
	•	ProfileView.vue
	•	Each view should render a simple heading indicating where the user is (e.g. "Journal (placeholder)").
	3.	App Shell Layout
	•	Implement a root AppShell layout that will wrap all views:
	•	Top app bar (AppTopAppBar component – required):
	•	Displays the app name (placeholder is fine).
	•	Bottom navigation bar (AppBottomNav component – required):
	•	Five navigation items:
	•	Today
	•	Journal
	•	Emotions
	•	Exercises
	•	Profile
	•	Uses Vue Router router-link or programmatic navigation.
	•	Ensure the main content area correctly renders the current route below the top bar and above the bottom nav.
	4.	Material Design Base Components
	•	Implement a small, reusable set of base components styled with Tailwind but following Material Design 3 principles:
	•	AppButton:
	•	Props: variant (e.g. "filled" | "outlined" | "text" | "tonal"), disabled, and default slot.
	•	Applies appropriate rounded corners, elevation (where applicable), and hover/press states.
	•	AppCard:
	•	Simple container with rounded corners, subtle elevation or border, padding.
	•	AppTopAppBar and AppBottomNav as structured components using AppButton internally (required for this story).
	•	Introduce theme tokens via CSS variables in a global stylesheet (e.g. :root):
	•	--color-primary
	•	--color-on-primary
	•	--color-surface
	•	--color-surface-variant
	•	--color-outline
	•	Wire these variables into Tailwind configuration via `theme.extend.colors` in tailwind.config.js/ts:
	•	Map Material Design tokens to Tailwind color utilities (e.g. `primary: 'var(--color-primary)'`).
	•	This allows components to use Material color roles consistently throughout the app (e.g. `bg-primary`, `text-on-primary`).

⸻

Acceptance Criteria
	•	The app starts into a layout with:
	•	A top app bar at the top.
	•	A bottom navigation bar with 5 items.
	•	A main content area that changes based on the active route.
	•	Clicking each bottom navigation item updates the URL and renders the corresponding placeholder view (/today, /journal, /emotions, /exercises, /profile).
	•	Base components (AppButton, AppCard) exist and:
	•	Are used at least once somewhere in the shell (e.g. top bar actions, a sample card in one view) to validate styling and behavior.
	•	Visually follow a Material Design–inspired style (rounded corners, clear hover/pressed states, primary color usage).
	•	Lint and TypeScript checks pass (no new linting or type errors introduced).

⸻

Out of Scope
	•	Any journal-specific domain logic (models, persistence, stores).
	•	Emotion system, exercises, profile logic.
	•	PWA configuration or offline behavior.
	•	Advanced theming (dark mode, dynamic colors).

⸻